# Initial EDA

## Target Distribution

```{r eda-target}
train |>
  count(dep_del15) |>
  mutate(pct = round(100 * n / sum(n), 1)) |>
  rename(delayed = dep_del15)

train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(dep_del15, labels = c("On time", "Delayed ≥15 min")))) +
  geom_bar(fill = c("steelblue", "tomato"), width = 0.5) +
  geom_text(stat = "count", aes(label = after_stat(count)), vjust = -0.4) +
  labs(title = "Departure delay distribution (PIT departures, 2023–2024)",
       x = NULL, y = "Flights") +
  theme_minimal()
```

The classes are imbalanced — roughly 80/20 on-time vs. delayed. This is
typical for flight data and worth keeping in mind when choosing a threshold
for binary predictions (defaulting to 0.5 will bias toward predicting on-time).
AUC is our actual metric so this matters less for model selection, but it's
relevant if we need calibrated probabilities or set a custom threshold.

## Missingness

```{r eda-missing}
train |>
  summarise(across(everything(), ~ mean(is.na(.)))) |>
  pivot_longer(everything(), names_to = "variable", values_to = "pct_missing") |>
  filter(pct_missing > 0) |>
  arrange(desc(pct_missing)) |>
  mutate(pct_missing = round(100 * pct_missing, 2)) |>
  print(n = 40)
```

Most missingness is in the delay-reason columns (carrier delay, weather delay,
etc.), which we can't use for prediction anyway. What matters is whether any
pre-departure features we plan to use — distance, CRS times, tail number —
have meaningful missingness. Those would need imputation or a missingness
indicator before modelling.

## Delay Rate by Carrier

```{r eda-carrier}
train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(op_unique_carrier) |>
  summarise(n_flights  = n(),
            delay_rate = mean(dep_del15),
            .groups = "drop") |>
  arrange(desc(delay_rate)) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(op_unique_carrier, delay_rate), y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  geom_text(aes(label = scales::percent(delay_rate, accuracy = 1)),
            hjust = -0.1, size = 3) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent, limits = c(0, 0.5)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by carrier (PIT departures, 2023–2024)",
       x = "Carrier", y = "Proportion delayed ≥15 min") +
  theme_minimal()
```

There's meaningful variation across carriers, so carrier should be a useful
predictor. Be cautious with carriers that have very few flights at PIT — their
delay rates will be noisy and could overfit. Consider smoothing small-volume
carriers toward the overall mean or grouping them into an "other" category.

## Delay Rate by Month

```{r eda-month}
train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(month) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), n = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = month, y = delay_rate, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_point(aes(size = n), color = "steelblue") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = month.abb) +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by month",
       x = "Month", y = "Proportion delayed", size = "# flights") +
  theme_minimal()
```

Delay rates peak in summer (June–August) and around the winter holidays
(December), consistent with high-traffic periods and weather. Spring and fall
are lower-risk. The seasonal pattern also suggests that weather data (if we
add it) would have the most impact in winter and summer months.

## Delay Rate by Day of Week

```{r eda-dow}
train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15)) |>
  group_by(day_of_week) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = day_of_week, y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by day of week", x = NULL, y = "Proportion delayed") +
  theme_minimal()
```

The day-of-week effect is real but modest. Thursdays and Fridays tend to be
slightly worse, likely due to higher traffic as people travel for weekends.
Saturdays are often the most punctual day, consistent with lower overall demand.
Useful as a feature but probably not a top predictor on its own — most valuable
in combination with hour and month.

## Delay Rate by Scheduled Departure Hour

```{r eda-hour}
train |>
  filter(!is.na(dep_del15), !is.na(sched_dep_hour)) |>
  group_by(sched_dep_hour) |>
  summarise(delay_rate = mean(dep_del15), n = n(), .groups = "drop") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = sched_dep_hour, y = delay_rate)) +
  geom_line(color = "steelblue") +
  geom_point(aes(size = n), color = "steelblue") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(5, 23, 2)) +
  labs(title = "Delay rate by scheduled departure hour",
       x = "Scheduled departure hour", y = "Proportion delayed", size = "# flights") +
  theme_minimal()
```

This is probably the strongest single signal we have. Delays increase steadily
through the day and peak in the evening — the classic delay cascade, where a
late plane from an earlier leg ripples forward. Early morning departures (5–7am)
are the most punctual since aircraft are freshly repositioned overnight.
`sched_dep_hour` should be a top feature in any model we try.

## Top Destinations from PIT

```{r eda-dest}
train |>
  count(dest, sort = TRUE) |>
  slice_head(n = 15) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(dest, n), y = n)) +
  geom_col(fill = "steelblue") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 15 destinations from PIT (2023–2024)",
       x = "Destination", y = "Number of flights") +
  theme_minimal()
```

The dominant routes are hubs (ORD, ATL, CLT, etc.), which makes sense for a
mid-size airport like PIT. Hub routes see more traffic and are more exposed to
system-wide delays. It's worth checking whether delay rates differ meaningfully
by destination — flights into congested hubs may be more likely to be held.
Route-level delay rates could be a useful engineered feature down the line.

